<dl id="n42048f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42048f">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42048f"> 48(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hennifs / = incliners <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42048f"><li>FW 128.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n42048f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n42048f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42048f">MS BL 47475-229</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:260 <a name="fad6y" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fad6y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad6.htm#n42048f">Draft: I.6&sect;1.6</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">the more thoughtful minds, tinged with traditions of Judaism, were seeking for what they called the &ldquo;religion of Abraham.&rdquo; These men were called &ldquo;<mark>Hanifs</mark>&rdquo; or &ldquo;<mark>incliners</mark>,&rdquo; and their religion seems to have consisted chiefly in &hellip; denying the superstition of the Arabs, and in only asserting the existence of one sole-ruling God <small> Stanley Lane-Poole, <a name="SLPS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SLPS"><cite title="source">The Speeches and Table-Talk of the Prophet Mohammad</cite></a> (1882) xxv</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
